\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5635086|God's Own Country}}\n* {{Mojo title|godsowncountry|God's Own Country}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|gods_own_country_2017|God's Own Country}}\n* {{Metacritic film|gods-own-country|God's Own Country}}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/apr/28/countryside-the-levelling-gods-own-country-abandon-inner-city ''Guardian'' article from April 2017 about the film and fellow \"countryside movie\" ''The Levelling'']\n\n{{BIFA BestBritishFilm}}\n{{Empire Award for Best British Film}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Motion Picture}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:God's Own Country}}\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:2010s independent films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:British coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:British LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:British romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age romance films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about immigration]]\n[[Category:Films set in Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Gay-related films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related romance films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:Orion Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Romanian films]]\n[[Category:Samuel Goldwyn Films films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 film by Francis Lee}}\n{{use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = God's Own Country\n| image = God's Own Country (2017 film).png\n| caption = British release poster\n| director = [[Francis Lee (director)|Francis Lee]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Manon Ardisson\n* Jack Tarling\n}}\n| writer = Francis Lee\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Josh O'Connor]]\n* [[Alec Sec\u0103reanu]]\n* [[Ian Hart]]\n* [[Gemma Jones]]\n}}\n| music = [[A Winged Victory for the Sullen]]\n| cinematography = Joshua James Richards\n| editing = Chris Wyatt\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n*British Film Institute\n*Creative England\n*Met Film Production\n*Shudder Films\n*Inflammable Films\n*Magic Bear Productions\n}}\n| distributor = {{ubl|[[Orion Pictures]]<br/>[[Samuel Goldwyn Films]]<br />{{Small|(United States)}}|[[Picturehouse Entertainment]]<br />{{Small|(United Kingdom)}}}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|2017|1|23|Sundance|2017|9|1|United Kingdom|2017|10|25|United States}}\n| runtime = 105 minutes<ref name=\":SI:\">{{cite web|title=God's Own Country|url=https://www.sundance.org/projects/god-s-own-country|website=www.sundance.org|publisher=Sundance Institute|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| budget = \u00a31 million<ref name=\":INEWS:\" />\n| gross = $2.6 million<ref name=\"TN\"/><ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''God's Own Country''''' is a 2017 British drama film written and directed by [[Francis Lee (director)|Francis Lee]] in his feature directorial debut. The film stars [[Josh O'Connor]] and [[Alec Sec\u0103reanu]]. The plot follows a young sheep farmer in [[Yorkshire]] whose life is transformed by a Romanian migrant worker. \n\nUpon release, the film received widespread acclaim from critics, who praised the performances (particularly O\u2019Connor\u2019s) and story, as well as commending it as a promising start for Lee. It was the only UK-based production to feature in the world drama category at the 2017 [[Sundance Film Festival]], where it won the world cinema directing award.\n\n==Plot==\nIn [[Yorkshire]], Johnny lives on the family farm with his father, Martin, and grandmother, Deirdre. Due to his father having suffered from a stroke, and his grandmother's age, much of the day-to-day running of the farm falls to Johnny. In his social time, Johnny engages in binge drinking and furtive sexual encounters with other men. Returning late to the farm after such an encounter with a young auctioneer, he is berated by his father because a calf has died from a [[breech birth]] in his absence.\n\nGheorghe, a Romanian migrant worker, is hired as extra help for the [[lambing season]]. He arrives and spends his first night in a caravan that the family has organised as his accommodation. As the [[Sheep|ewes]] have moved away from the main part of the farm, and as part of the farm's boundary wall remains unrepaired by Johnny, it is decided that Johnny and Gheorghe should spend several days camping nearer to the animals. When one of the ewes gives birth to an unconscious runt, Johnny is intrigued when Gheorghe is able to resuscitate and care for it. One morning, after Johnny refers to Gheorghe yet again as a \"[[gypsy]]\", Gheorghe tackles him to the ground and warns Johnny not to speak that way to him again.\n\nThe next day, the two men again engage in a fight which results in Johnny performing fellatio on Gheorghe and the two men have rough and passionate sex in the dirt. While Johnny initially does not acknowledge the encounter, the two share cigarettes and a sugar packet<ref>{{cite web\n | url =http://anthemmagazine.com/screen-test-alec-secareanu/\n | title =Screen Test: Alec Secareanu\n | last =Chang\n | first =Kee\n | date =26 October 2017\n | website =Anthem Magazine\n | publisher =\n | access-date =4 March 2018 | quote = \"We see that echoed around the campfire when he sneaks packets of sugar into his instant rice cups, right? I thought it was drugs at first.\" \"Yes, it's sugar packets. That\u2019s what keeps him going.\"}}</ref> for their [[cup noodles]] throughout the day. That night, Gheorghe resists Johnny's aggressive move to have sex, instead patiently showing him that sex can also be tender, and the two men kiss for the first time.\n\nReturning to the farm, Johnny invites Gheorghe to stay with him in the house, but Gheorghe elects to remain in the caravan. When Martin suffers a second stroke, Johnny realises that the running of the farm is now entirely his responsibility, and asks Gheorghe if he will stay with him. When Gheorghe expresses uncertainty over whether they can stay together and maintain the farm simultaneously, Johnny reacts poorly, drinking to excess and engaging in another random sexual encounter. When Gheorghe realises what Johnny has done, he abruptly leaves the farm.\n\nMartin is released from the hospital but is now fully debilitated. Johnny, desperate to make up with Gheorghe, tells his father that he will stay to run the farm, but that things must be run on his terms. Martin gives his tacit approval to Johnny, who sets off to bring Gheorghe back to the farm. After he finds Gheorghe working in [[Scotland]], the two men reconcile. Gheorghe returns with Johnny; the caravan is taken away, and Gheorghe moves into the house.<ref name=\":TA:\">{{cite news|last1=Rahman|first1=Miran|title=Planned feature film could receive key funding support|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/11399303.Planned_feature_film_could_receive_key_funding_support/|accessdate=11 January 2017|work=Bradford Telegraph and Argus|date=9 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\":BFI:\">{{cite web|title=British Council Film: God's Own Country|url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/gods-own-country|website=film.britishcouncil.org|publisher=British Film Council|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n<!-- Cast is listed alphabetically until film has been given a full release and the cast list is given -->\n* [[Josh O'Connor]] as Johnny Saxby\n* [[Alec Sec\u0103reanu]] as Gheorghe Ionescu\n* [[Ian Hart]] as Martin Saxby\n* [[Gemma Jones]] as Deirdre Saxby<ref>{{cite web|title=God's Own Country full cast and crew|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5635086/fullcredits|website=imdb.com|accessdate=11 January 2017|date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe film is partly based on writer and director Francis Lee's own life, where he also had to make a decision to either stay and work on his family's farm or go off to drama school.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rosser|first1=Michael|title='God's Own Country' cast revealed as shoot begins|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/gods-own-country-cast-revealed-as-shoot-begins/5101798.article#|website=screendaily.com|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film was shot in Yorkshire, specifically around the [[Silsden]] area of [[Keighley]] in [[West Yorkshire]],<ref name=\":TA:\" /> with some other scenes being shot in [[Keighley Bus Station]]<ref name=\":KN:\">{{cite news|last1=Knights|first1=David|title=New movie God's Own Country filmed at Keighley bus station|url=http://www.keighleynews.co.uk/news/14462790.New_movie_God_s_Own_Country_filmed_at_Keighley_bus_station/|accessdate=11 January 2017|work=Keighley News|date=29 April 2016}}</ref> and [[Airedale General Hospital]] with [[Haworth]] and [[Otley]] also featuring as backdrops for the film.<ref name=\":KN:\" />\n\nThe production was financed in part through the British Film Council's iFeature programme with additional funding being secured from Creative England.<ref name=\":BFI:\" />\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] on 23 January 2017. It was the only production from the United Kingdom that featured in the world drama category in the 2017 Sundance Film Festival.<ref name=\":INEWS:\">{{cite news|last1=Sherwin|first1=Adam|title=Sundance Film Festival to premiere Yorkshire sheep farming movie|url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/culture/film/sundance-film-festival-chooses-yorkshire-sheep-farming-movie-world-premiere/|accessdate=11 January 2017|work=iNews|date=1 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shudder Films' First Completed Feature Selected for Premiere at Sundance \u2039 News and Opportunities \u2039 Homepage|url=http://northernmedia.org/news/shudder-films-first-completed-feature-selected-for-premiere-at-sundance|website=NFM|accessdate=11 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118052040/http://northernmedia.org/news/shudder-films-first-completed-feature-selected-for-premiere-at-sundance|archive-date=18 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> It went onto screen at the [[Berlin International Film Festival]] on 11 February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/programm/berlinale_programm/datenblatt.php?film_id=201711895#tab=video25|title=God's Own Country|website=[[Berlin International Film Festival]]|accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/berlin-rounds-out-panorama-lineup-call-me-by-your-name-luca-guadagnino-armie-hammer-sundance-gods-own-country-1201893790/|title=Berlin Rounds Out Panorama Lineup, Adds 'Call Me By Your Name' & 'God's Own Country'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Diana|last=Lodderhose|date=6 February 2017|accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nShortly after, [[Picturehouse Entertainment]], [[Orion Pictures]] and [[Samuel Goldwyn Films]] acquired UK and US distribution rights respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/picturehouse-takes-sundance-hit-gods-own-country-for-uk/5114607.article|title=Picturehouse takes Sundance hit 'God's Own Country' for UK|website=[[Screen International]]|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=6 February 2017|accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/orion-pictures-samuel-goldwyn-films-acquire-gods-own-country-1202086652/|title=Orion Pictures, Samuel Goldwyn Films Land 'God's Own Country' For U.S.|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|date=8 May 2017|accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref> It was released in the United Kingdom on 1 September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/gods-own-country-to-open-edinburgh-film-festival-1202419463/|title='God's Own Country,' Gay Love Story That Premiered at Sundance, to Open Edinburgh Film Festival|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Robert|last=Mitchell|date=9 May 2017|accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref> The film was banned in some [[Arab countries]] due to explicit sex scenes between the two protagonists.<ref name=\"interzis\">{{cite web |url=https://www.click.ro/vedete/romanesti/film-cu-romani-interzis-unele-tari-din-cauza-scenelor-prea-deocheate |title=Film cu rom\u00e2ni, interzis \u00een unele \u021b\u0103ri din cauza scenelor prea deocheate |work=Click! |author=Gheorghe Chelu |date=16 November 2017 |language=Romanian}}</ref> Likewise, [[Romania]] was the only country in [[Eastern Europe]] where the film was screened.<ref name=\"interzis\" />\n\n''God's Own Country'' was released on DVD on 30 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/dvd-blu-ray-release-calendar-january-2018|title=DVD/Blu-ray Release Calendar - January 2018|website=[[Metacritic]]|date=31 December 2017|last1=Dietz|first1=Jason|last2=Kimbell|first2=Keith|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2018|3|8}}, ''God's Own Country'' has grossed a worldwide total of $2.6 million, which includes $1.2 million in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"TN\">{{cite web|title=God's Own Country (2017)|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Gods-Own-Country-(UK)#tab=summary|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2550302209/|title=God's Own Country|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:Josh O'Connor at the 6th Odessa International Film Festival (4).jpg|thumb|O'Connor's performance was praised by critics.|upright]]\n''God's Own Country'' received critical acclaim. The film holds a 98% approval rating based on 122 reviews, with a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 7.96/10, on the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. The site's critical consensus reads: \"A quiet, moving rumination on loneliness and newfound intimacy, ''God's Own Country'' marks an outstanding directorial debut for Francis Lee.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/gods_own_country_2017/|title=God's Own Country|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a rating of 85 out of 100, based on 22 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/gods-own-country|title=God's Own Country|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Sundance Film Festival's listing for ''God's Own Country'' says that \"you can smell the mud in this movie\" while also describing Francis Lee as a major new talent and the film as \"one not to be missed.\"<ref name=\":SI:\" /> [[Peter Bradshaw]], writing in ''The Guardian'', gave the film four stars out of five. Bradshaw described the film as \"an almost, but not quite a Dales ''[[Brokeback Mountain|Brokeback]],''\" and also as a \"very British love story, bursting at the seams with unspoken emotions, unvoiced fears about the future, and a readiness to displace every emotion into hard physical work\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=Peter|title=God's Own Country review \u2013 Dales answer to Brokeback that's a very British love story|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jan/22/gods-own-country-review-a-dales-answer-to-brokeback-thats-a-very-british-love-story|accessdate=29 January 2017|work=The Guardian|date=22 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2017 Berlin International Film Festival]] the film received the Harvey Award, presented by the [[Teddy Awards]] programme for LGBT-related films in conjunction with a reader jury from the German LGBT magazine ''[[M\u00e4nner (magazine)|M\u00e4nner]]''.<ref name=\"Harvey\"/>\n\nEd Potton, writing in ''The Times'', gave the film four stars out of five and described the film as \"splendid\" and \"[a] potent film, a Yorkshire ''Brokeback Mountain''\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Potton|first1=Ed|title=It's Brokeback on the moors|work=The Times|issue=72317|date=1 September 2017|location=Times 2|page=8|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s) and nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"1\"| [[Australian Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 13 March 2018\n| Best International Film (English Language)\n| ''God's Own Country''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|title=The 2018 AFCA Awards|url=http://www.afca.org.au/afca-2018-film--writing-awards.html|publisher=[[Australian Film Critics Association]]|accessdate=28 February 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314095057/http://www.afca.org.au/afca-2018-film--writing-awards.html|archivedate=14 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[67th Berlin International Film Festival|18 February 2017]]\n| {{lang|de|[[M\u00e4nner (magazine)|M\u00e4nner]]}} Jury Award\n| ''God's Own Country''\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|<ref name=\"Harvey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sebastian-lelios-a-fantastic-woman-wins-berlin-film-festivals-lgbt-honor-teddy-977544|title=Berlin: Sebastian Lelio's ''A Fantastic Woman'' Wins Teddy Award for Best Film|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=18 February 2017|accessdate=18 February 2017|first=Scott|last=Roxborough}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.teddyaward.tv/en/2017/01/31/all-films-at-the-31st-teddy-award/|title=All Films At The 31st Teddy Award |publisher=[[Teddy Award]] |accessdate=17 October 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720105614/http://blog.teddyaward.tv/en/2017/01/31/all-films-at-the-31st-teddy-award/|archivedate=20 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\